Note:
Runtime dependency (DAG) task-scheduler API — the public data-flow scheduler
for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. It schedules a TASK GRAPH rather than
a flat queue: each task may declare prerequisite tasks, and a task only becomes
eligible to run once EVERY one of its prerequisites has completed. It is
therefore distinct from two neighbouring facilities it composes on top of:

  - the thread pool (thread_pool.runa) is a flat FIFO executor with no notion
    of ordering between the functions it runs; this scheduler decides WHICH
    tasks are runnable and WHEN, then hands each runnable task to the pool.
  - a single-value future carries one result from producer to consumer; this
    scheduler coordinates a whole graph of tasks and the happens-before edges
    between them.

It adds no new locking or thread mechanism of its own. It composes three
already-complete lower layers:

  - EXECUTION comes from the runtime thread pool (pool_new / pool_submit /
    pool_shutdown). Every runnable task is submitted to the pool, which runs it
    on one of its worker threads via the module-level scheduler_task_trampoline
    entry point (its address is taken with the $name function-pointer operator,
    exactly as the thread pool spawns its own workers).
  - MUTUAL EXCLUSION over all task bookkeeping — every task's pending-prereq
    counter and state, the task array, and the remaining-task counter — comes
    from a single runtime RuntimeMutex (mutex.runa). One lock serialises every
    read-modify-write of the graph state so cascades from concurrently
    completing tasks can never race.
  - COMPLETION COORDINATION comes from one runtime RuntimeCondVar
    (condition_variable.runa) paired with that single mutex: scheduler_run
    blocks on it while the remaining-task counter is above zero, and the
    trampoline broadcasts it exactly when the counter reaches zero. Per the
    condvar contract, the RuntimeMutex object handle is passed to condvar_wait
    (it extracts the inner sync_core handle at offset 0), and the wait is
    wrapped in a predicate loop so a broadcast re-checks the shared state.

DATA-FLOW MODEL. Building the graph and running it are two phases:

  1. BUILD (single caller): scheduler_add_task registers a task body and its
     argument; scheduler_add_dependency records a "task depends on prereq" edge
     by incrementing the dependent's pending-prereq count and appending the
     dependent to the prereq's dependents list. Both must complete before
     scheduler_run is called.
  2. RUN: scheduler_run submits every task that starts with zero pending
     prerequisites, then blocks until every task is done. Each time a task
     finishes, the trampoline decrements the pending-prereq count of each of
     its dependents; any dependent whose count reaches zero is itself submitted
     (the cascade). When the count of not-yet-done tasks reaches zero the
     trampoline broadcasts the completion condvar and scheduler_run returns.

EXACTLY-ONCE EXECUTION. A task is submitted only on the single state
transition WAITING -> SUBMITTED, and that transition is performed under the
lock guarded by a check that the task is still WAITING, so no task can be
submitted twice even if two prerequisites finish simultaneously. Each task's
completion decrements the remaining counter exactly once, so the counter
reaches zero precisely when every task has run once.

CONTEXT OWNERSHIP. Each task owns a single TaskRunCtx {sched, task}, allocated
when the task is added and freed at shutdown. That one context is the argument
passed to the pool for that task's single submission — whether the initial
submission from scheduler_run or the cascaded submission from the trampoline —
so the run path performs no per-submission allocation and has no allocation
failure mode that could strand a runnable task.

Task layout (64 bytes):
    offset  0:  fn         — task body function pointer
    offset  8:  arg        — opaque argument passed to the body
    offset 16:  pending    — count of prerequisites not yet completed
    offset 24:  state      — 0 waiting, 1 submitted, 2 done
    offset 32:  deps       — pointer to the dependents array (Task pointers)
    offset 40:  dep_count  — number of dependents recorded
    offset 48:  dep_cap    — dependents array capacity in slots
    offset 56:  ctx        — pointer to this task's TaskRunCtx

Scheduler layout (56 bytes):
    offset  0:  pool       — the runtime thread pool that executes tasks
    offset  8:  mutex      — RuntimeMutex guarding all task bookkeeping
    offset 16:  tasks      — pointer to the all-tasks array (Task pointers)
    offset 24:  task_count — number of tasks registered
    offset 32:  task_cap   — all-tasks array capacity in slots
    offset 40:  remaining  — count of tasks not yet completed
    offset 48:  condvar    — RuntimeCondVar broadcast when remaining hits zero

TaskRunCtx layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  sched  — the owning scheduler
    offset 8:  task   — the task this submission runs
:End Note

Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/condition_variable.runa" as CondVar
Import "runtime/concurrency/threading/thread_pool.runa" as Pool
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: Task object layout
Constant TASK_SIZE as Integer is 64
Constant TASK_OFF_FN as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_OFF_ARG as Integer is 8
Constant TASK_OFF_PENDING as Integer is 16
Constant TASK_OFF_STATE as Integer is 24
Constant TASK_OFF_DEPS as Integer is 32
Constant TASK_OFF_DEP_COUNT as Integer is 40
Constant TASK_OFF_DEP_CAP as Integer is 48
Constant TASK_OFF_CTX as Integer is 56

Note: Task state values
Constant TASK_STATE_WAITING as Integer is 0
Constant TASK_STATE_SUBMITTED as Integer is 1
Constant TASK_STATE_DONE as Integer is 2

Note: Scheduler object layout
Constant SCHED_SIZE as Integer is 56
Constant SCHED_OFF_POOL as Integer is 0
Constant SCHED_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 8
Constant SCHED_OFF_TASKS as Integer is 16
Constant SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT as Integer is 24
Constant SCHED_OFF_TASK_CAP as Integer is 32
Constant SCHED_OFF_REMAINING as Integer is 40
Constant SCHED_OFF_CONDVAR as Integer is 48

Note: TaskRunCtx object layout
Constant CTX_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant CTX_OFF_SCHED as Integer is 0
Constant CTX_OFF_TASK as Integer is 8

Note: Size of one pointer slot in the growable task and dependents arrays
Constant PTR_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note: Initial capacities in slots; each array doubles on demand when full
Constant SCHED_INITIAL_TASK_CAP as Integer is 64
Constant TASK_INITIAL_DEP_CAP as Integer is 4

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime task-scheduler API
Constant SCHED_OK as Integer is 0
Constant SCHED_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant SCHED_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 2

Process called "scheduler_task_trampoline" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The per-task entry point every worker runs. It has two jobs that must be
    kept strictly apart: execute the task body, which may be arbitrarily long
    and must not hold any scheduler lock so sibling tasks run in parallel; and
    then, under the single scheduler lock, account for the task's completion and
    propagate its effect through the graph. That propagation is the cascade —
    the only place new tasks become runnable — so the ordering guarantee of the
    whole scheduler lives in this function.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the owning scheduler and this task from the context, then run the body
    with call_indirect_1(fn, arg) holding no lock. Re-acquire the scheduler
    mutex and mark the task done. Walk its dependents: for each, decrement the
    dependent's pending-prerequisite count; when that count reaches zero and the
    dependent is still WAITING, transition it to SUBMITTED and hand its own
    pre-allocated context to the pool. The pool has its own independent lock, so
    submitting while holding the scheduler lock is safe and never inverts. The
    two conditions (count reached zero, dependent still waiting) are expressed as
    nested checks rather than a compound predicate. Finally decrement the
    scheduler's remaining-task counter; if it reaches zero, broadcast the
    completion condvar so scheduler_run can return, then release the lock.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One indirect call for the body outside any lock, then one short critical
    section proportional to the task's dependent count. The context is reused
    from the task, so the completion path performs no allocation. Cascaded
    submissions each cost one pool_submit (a single enqueue plus one futex wake).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null context returns immediately. The function pointer invoked is the one
    supplied when the task was added; this layer performs the indirect call
    faithfully and does not validate the target, matching call_indirect_1's
    contract. The scheduler lock is always released before return.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sched be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ctx, CTX_OFF_SCHED
    Let task be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ctx, CTX_OFF_TASK
    Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_FN
    Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_ARG

    Note: Run the task body with no lock held so other tasks proceed in parallel.
    proc call_indirect_1 from Call with fn, arg

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CONDVAR
    Let pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_POOL
    Let trampoline_fn be $scheduler_task_trampoline

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Note: Mark this task done, then cascade to every dependent it unblocks.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_DONE

    Let deps be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_DEPS
    Let dep_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_DEP_COUNT
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than dep_count:
        Let dep_slot be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let dep be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with deps, dep_slot
        Let dep_pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dep, TASK_OFF_PENDING
        Let dep_pending_after be dep_pending minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dep, TASK_OFF_PENDING, dep_pending_after
        If dep_pending_after is equal to 0:
            Let dep_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dep, TASK_OFF_STATE
            If dep_state is equal to TASK_STATE_WAITING:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dep, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_SUBMITTED
                Let dep_ctx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dep, TASK_OFF_CTX
                proc pool_submit from Pool with pool, trampoline_fn, dep_ctx
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Account for this task's completion; wake scheduler_run when all done.
    Let remaining be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING
    Let remaining_after be remaining minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING, remaining_after
    If remaining_after is equal to 0:
        proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "scheduler_new" takes worker_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a ready-to-use dependency scheduler. It owns exactly the resources
    it composes: a thread pool to run tasks, one mutex to serialise graph
    bookkeeping, one condvar to signal whole-graph completion, and a growable
    array of the tasks it will manage. Construction acquires each resource in
    order and only returns a scheduler once every one is in place.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the scheduler object, then create the pool (passing worker_count
    straight through so the pool applies its own hardware-concurrency default for
    non-positive values), the mutex, the condvar, and the initial task array. On
    any failure, unwind exactly the resources already acquired — shutting down
    the pool, destroying the mutex/condvar as applicable — and return 0.
    Initialise the task count and remaining counter to zero and the capacity to
    the initial size.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path: one pool construction (which spawns the worker threads), one
    mutex and one condvar creation, and two allocations. Done once per graph.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Every allocation and creation is checked; partial failure frees what was
    acquired and returns 0 (NULL), so callers MUST check the result before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sched be proc allocate from Memory with SCHED_SIZE
    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pool be proc pool_new from Pool with worker_count
    If pool is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with sched
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc pool_shutdown from Pool with pool
        proc deallocate from Memory with sched
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cv be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
        proc pool_shutdown from Pool with pool
        proc deallocate from Memory with sched
        Return 0
    End If

    Let task_bytes be SCHED_INITIAL_TASK_CAP multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    Let tasks be proc allocate from Memory with task_bytes
    If tasks is equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
        proc pool_shutdown from Pool with pool
        proc deallocate from Memory with sched
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_POOL, pool
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS, tasks
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_CAP, SCHED_INITIAL_TASK_CAP
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CONDVAR, cv
    Return sched
End Process

Process called "scheduler_add_task" takes sched as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Register one task in the graph without running it. A task begins with no
    prerequisites and no dependents; edges are added afterwards by
    scheduler_add_dependency. The returned pointer is the task's stable identity,
    used as the handle to name it in dependency edges. Because the run phase must
    never fail to submit a runnable task for lack of a context, each task's
    single TaskRunCtx is allocated here, up front, alongside the task.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the task object, its initial dependents array, and its context.
    Initialise the body pointer and argument, a zero pending-prereq count, the
    WAITING state, an empty dependents list at initial capacity, and the context
    pointer; populate the context with the scheduler and the task. Then, under
    the scheduler mutex, append the task to the all-tasks array — doubling that
    array first if it is full, copying the live entries into the larger buffer —
    increment the task count and the remaining-task counter, and release the
    lock. Any allocation failure frees exactly what was allocated and returns
    the allocation error.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three small allocations plus one array append. The append is amortised O(1):
    the all-tasks array doubles, so total copy work is linear in tasks added.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. Every allocation is checked and
    unwound on failure, and the lock is released on every return path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let task be proc allocate from Memory with TASK_SIZE
    If task is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
    End If

    Let dep_bytes be TASK_INITIAL_DEP_CAP multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    Let deps be proc allocate from Memory with dep_bytes
    If deps is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with task
        Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
    End If

    Let ctx be proc allocate from Memory with CTX_SIZE
    If ctx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with deps
        proc deallocate from Memory with task
        Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_FN, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_ARG, arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_PENDING, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_WAITING
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_DEPS, deps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_DEP_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_DEP_CAP, TASK_INITIAL_DEP_CAP
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_CTX, ctx

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ctx, CTX_OFF_SCHED, sched
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ctx, CTX_OFF_TASK, task

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_CAP
    If count is equal to cap:
        Note: All-tasks array is full — grow it to double capacity.
        Let old_arr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS
        Let new_cap be cap multiplied by 2
        Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let new_arr be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
        If new_arr is equal to 0:
            proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
            proc deallocate from Memory with ctx
            proc deallocate from Memory with deps
            proc deallocate from Memory with task
            Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
        End If
        Let copy_bytes be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_copy from Memory with new_arr, old_arr, copy_bytes
        proc deallocate from Memory with old_arr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS, new_arr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_CAP, new_cap
    End If

    Let arr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS
    Let slot_off be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with arr, slot_off, task
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT, count plus 1

    Let remaining be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING, remaining plus 1

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return task
End Process

Process called "scheduler_add_dependency" takes sched as Integer, task as Integer, prereq as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Record one happens-before edge: task must not run until prereq has completed.
    An edge has two effects that must both be published atomically — the
    dependent gains one more prerequisite it is waiting on, and the prerequisite
    gains one more dependent to notify when it finishes — so the whole update is
    performed under the scheduler lock. Edges must be added during the build
    phase, before scheduler_run submits anything.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the scheduler mutex, increment the dependent's pending-prerequisite
    count, then append the dependent to the prerequisite's dependents array,
    doubling that array first if it is full and copying the live entries across.
    If the grow allocation fails, roll the pending increment back so the edge is
    recorded all-or-nothing, release the lock, and return the allocation error.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One counter increment and one array append under the lock. The dependents
    array doubles on demand, so appends are amortised O(1) in the number of
    dependents.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null scheduler, task, or prerequisite returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. On the grow
    failure path the pending count is restored so no half-recorded edge is left
    behind, and the lock is released on every return path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If task is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If prereq is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_PENDING
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_PENDING, pending plus 1

    Let dcount be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEP_COUNT
    Let dcap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEP_CAP
    If dcount is equal to dcap:
        Note: Dependents array is full — grow it to double capacity.
        Let old_deps be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEPS
        Let new_dcap be dcap multiplied by 2
        Let new_dbytes be new_dcap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let new_deps be proc allocate from Memory with new_dbytes
        If new_deps is equal to 0:
            Note: Roll back the pending increment so the edge is all-or-nothing.
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with task, TASK_OFF_PENDING, pending
            proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
            Return SCHED_ERR_ALLOC
        End If
        Let dcopy_bytes be dcount multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_copy from Memory with new_deps, old_deps, dcopy_bytes
        proc deallocate from Memory with old_deps
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEPS, new_deps
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEP_CAP, new_dcap
    End If

    Let darr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEPS
    Let dslot be dcount multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with darr, dslot, task
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with prereq, TASK_OFF_DEP_COUNT, dcount plus 1

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_run" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drive the built graph to completion. The initial wavefront is every task
    that has no prerequisites; once those are running, completions cascade
    through the trampoline and make later tasks runnable, so scheduler_run's own
    job after seeding the wavefront is simply to block until the whole graph has
    drained.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the scheduler mutex once. Scan the all-tasks array and submit every
    task whose pending-prerequisite count is zero and whose state is still
    WAITING, transitioning each to SUBMITTED and handing its pre-allocated
    context to the pool; the zero-count and still-waiting conditions are checked
    as nested Ifs, not a compound predicate. Holding the lock across both the
    submissions and the first read of the remaining counter closes the
    lost-wakeup window: no worker can decrement remaining or broadcast until
    condvar_wait releases the lock. Then wait in a predicate loop — while
    remaining is above zero, condvar_wait on the completion condvar (passing the
    RuntimeMutex object, which it atomically releases and re-acquires) and
    re-read remaining after each wake. Release the lock once remaining is zero.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One linear scan of the task array to seed the wavefront, then the caller
    parks on the OS futex via condvar_wait with no busy-waiting until the graph
    completes. Submitting under the scheduler lock is safe because the pool has
    its own independent lock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. On return the lock is released and
    every task in the graph has run to completion exactly once.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CONDVAR
    Let pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_POOL
    Let trampoline_fn be $scheduler_task_trampoline

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Note: Seed the wavefront: submit every task that starts with no prerequisites.
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT
    Let arr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_off be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let cur be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arr, slot_off
        Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_PENDING
        If pending is equal to 0:
            Let cur_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_STATE
            If cur_state is equal to TASK_STATE_WAITING:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_STATE, TASK_STATE_SUBMITTED
                Let cur_ctx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_CTX
                proc pool_submit from Pool with pool, trampoline_fn, cur_ctx
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Block until every task has completed and remaining has reached zero.
    Let remaining be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING
    While remaining is greater than 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv, mtx
        Set remaining to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_REMAINING
    End While

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process

Process called "scheduler_task_count" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many tasks are registered in the graph, for diagnostics and for
    callers that size their own bookkeeping to the graph. Read under the lock so
    the count is a coherent snapshot rather than a torn read against a concurrent
    add.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the scheduler mutex, read the task-count field, release, and return
    it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex acquire/release and a single field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. Advisory: the count may change the
    instant the lock is released if tasks are still being added.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return count
End Process

Process called "scheduler_shutdown" takes sched as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stop and destroy the scheduler, releasing every resource it owns. The pool
    is shut down first so that once teardown of the graph state begins, no worker
    thread is left running the trampoline against tasks that are about to be
    freed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Shut the pool down (which drains and joins every worker). With no thread left
    touching the graph, free each task's dependents array, its context, and the
    task object itself, then free the all-tasks array, destroy the condvar and
    the mutex, and deallocate the scheduler object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path: one pool shutdown (joining the workers), one linear walk freeing
    three allocations per task, one condvar destroy, one mutex destroy, and two
    deallocations. Blocks until the pool has fully drained.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null scheduler returns SCHED_ERR_NULL. After this call the scheduler
    pointer is invalid and MUST NOT be reused. Calling it while scheduler_run is
    still blocked on the same scheduler is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If sched is equal to 0:
        Return SCHED_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_POOL
    proc pool_shutdown from Pool with pool

    Let arr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASKS
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_TASK_COUNT
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_off be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let cur be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with arr, slot_off
        If cur is not equal to 0:
            Let deps be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_DEPS
            If deps is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Memory with deps
            End If
            Let ctx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, TASK_OFF_CTX
            If ctx is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Memory with ctx
            End If
            proc deallocate from Memory with cur
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Memory with arr

    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_CONDVAR
    proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv
    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sched, SCHED_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
    proc deallocate from Memory with sched
    Return SCHED_OK
End Process
